00:45:35,460 --> 00:45:46,987
you know, for those of us that live in Medford, and actually we all live in a community somewhere, and for most of us, you know, we are literally not from the land that our town is on.

394
00:45:47,907 --> 00:45:57,113
And we walk around town, you know, just out on a walk yesterday, and it dawned on me that I don't know of any streets

395
00:45:57,834 --> 00:46:09,582
and I'm going to regret saying this, but very few streets, I'll say that, have any Italian names, yet Medford has like a massive history of like, it was an Italian town for a very long time.

396
00:46:10,362 --> 00:46:11,623
Well, why is that?

397
00:46:12,844 --> 00:46:17,727
Because people that were here before get to permanently be the definitions of the place.

398
00:46:18,608 --> 00:46:24,972
And I'm not sure if I'm getting my point across, but there's another little side point too is,

399
00:46:26,029 --> 00:46:36,456
You know the amount of the money of the bricks is certainly you know that's the thing, but we're sort of creating a here's a here's a list of people that mattered in Medford.

400
00:46:37,297 --> 00:46:44,542
Right, I mean when we walk to the library and see all those names if you don't know anything about Medford in the library you look down you'll say, these are people that.

401
00:46:46,228 --> 00:46:50,609
cared about Medford, mattered about Medford, had money to give in Medford.

402
00:46:52,089 --> 00:46:55,970
And there is an enormous amount of privilege in being able to do that.

403
00:46:56,190 --> 00:47:01,111
As member Hayes said, there's also an enormous amount of privilege to even know you could buy one, a brick.

404
00:47:01,971 --> 00:47:05,131
I mean, who bought the bricks at the library?

405
00:47:05,171 --> 00:47:14,513
The people who knew people who were on the library committee, who were elected office, you know, the teeny tiny segment of the population even knew they were available.

406
00:47:16,961 --> 00:47:19,203
That's almost certainly true.

407
00:47:20,264 --> 00:47:32,234
And everybody who essentially was connected and already in a better spot than a lot of other people, they're the only ones who even had the opportunity.

408
00:47:32,334 --> 00:47:40,301
So it just can create this weird pink, just like the street names, it creates this weird picture of a place that makes you think,

409
00:47:41,663 --> 00:47:53,908
that, well, I mean, I live in Orchard Street, so that's not a name of a person, but for all these names on our streets, other than the ones that became governors, like, who are these people?

410
00:47:57,949 --> 00:48:04,732
It doesn't feel welcoming either, and sort of this weird, like, hey, here's the group of people that matter here.

411
00:48:07,303 --> 00:48:08,604
I'm sounding really down on gifts.

412
00:48:09,064 --> 00:48:09,725
I do want gifts.

413
00:48:10,725 --> 00:48:17,789
I just want us to think through what it means to stick a name on something that doesn't belong to us.

414
00:48:17,849 --> 00:48:20,711
It doesn't belong to the school committee or any person in this meeting.

415
00:48:20,731 --> 00:48:21,711
It belongs to the public.

416
00:48:22,672 --> 00:48:33,078
And I just don't think we spend any energy thinking about, you know, we sometimes talk about public goods, you know, public education, the protection of the police and the fire.

417
00:48:33,118 --> 00:48:34,118
Those are all public goods.

418
00:48:36,053 --> 00:48:50,596
And I don't see anybody suggesting we name the fire stations or the police station or city hall, because it's so clear that that is public good and those are off limits.

419
00:48:51,096 --> 00:48:59,837
But then when we move into the schools, somehow it gets a little softer and we start deciding to just not do what they do in the rest of government.

420
00:48:59,877 --> 00:49:03,738
Although I know we have the Tip O'Neill building in Boston, so the federal government doesn't agree.

421
00:49:04,940 --> 00:49:07,482
I'll stop talking, we'll be here all night.

422
00:49:07,682 --> 00:49:22,234
Dr. Cushing, it's still possible to ask the architects to think about like an art installation space, is that right?

423
00:49:22,934 --> 00:49:23,815
Yes, yes.

424
00:49:23,895 --> 00:49:32,442
The final design is in process, but there are also enough perimeter spaces and the ultimate vision that

425
00:49:33,058 --> 00:49:42,063
The one thing that I've really wanted is to make sure that the walkway behind the building is as sealed off as possible, except for fire lane.

426
00:49:42,524 --> 00:49:56,812
So there will be spaces on either side of that, that now what I would consider only fire access and student access area where we could definitely have an art installation or anything along those lines.

427
00:49:57,012 --> 00:49:57,933
Also, I will say that

428
00:49:58,502 --> 00:50:05,586
the various departments and agencies of Medford and the mayor's office have committed to the funding for this program.

429
00:50:06,246 --> 00:50:21,455
And so anything additional from a brick or something along those lines would simply say, allow us to say, I don't know, install other benches or install maybe a bicycle rack that fits the vision of what we're looking for.

430
00:50:21,495 --> 00:50:27,358
We're working on that anyway for the McGlynn, but just trying to see if there are other ways that we can

431
00:50:28,315 --> 00:50:31,138
help to really tie this up with a really beautiful bow.

432
00:50:32,659 --> 00:50:39,124
So, you know, it's not a make a break, but I would say the bricks just stick with that idea for a second.

433
00:50:39,184 --> 00:50:41,186
I really appreciate what member Hayes said.

434
00:50:41,226 --> 00:50:42,347
I'd never thought of it that way.

435
00:50:42,387 --> 00:50:44,368
And it really helped to open my eyes.

436
00:50:44,388 --> 00:50:47,471
I have to say, I really appreciate that.

437
00:50:48,011 --> 00:50:56,058
So, you know, I see that as just an opportunity to remember a loved one or, and I know member McLaughlin has mentioned this a number of times,

438
00:50:56,615 --> 00:51:02,140
of a family who lost a child, and just as an opportunity to have that remembrance.

439
00:51:02,720 --> 00:51:09,346
But to go to your point, yes, we are still in the design phase where we can definitely add things to it.

440
00:51:12,048 --> 00:51:12,929
Thank you for that.

441
00:51:13,129 --> 00:51:13,910
Dr. Wardenson?

442
00:51:14,865 --> 00:51:25,508
Yes, I just wanted to weigh in when, Member Graham, you started sharing about potentially having an inclusive art experience.

443
00:51:25,729 --> 00:51:32,391
And right now, we are working on, I talked about it last week in last week's memo, the mosaic.

444
00:51:33,151 --> 00:51:38,953
And this past Wednesday, students went with our coordinator of fine arts, Suzanne Fee,

445
00:51:39,913 --> 00:51:45,175
and they're going to do a middle school day, and they're going to do a high school day as well.

446
00:51:46,035 --> 00:52:04,221
And so some of those mosaics, she shared with me, for families that weren't able to come to the high school to work during that time frame, they are going to provide some opportunities for additional pieces of the mosaics to go to the respective schools.

447
00:52:04,741 --> 00:52:07,582
So by the time this piece of art is completed,

448
00:52:09,422 --> 00:52:21,926
Students from all of the schools will have had an opportunity to at least, maybe not every single student but students will have had an opportunity to have participated in this beautiful mosaic that's going to be created.

449
00:52:22,326 --> 00:52:26,848
And so as you were talking about the different ways to include the community.

450
00:52:27,868 --> 00:52:45,883
and not thinking about cost per se, exception of the arts materials, I was thinking that that could be another beautiful way to beautify the space and have it be inclusive of the students and members of the community and

451
00:52:48,673 --> 00:52:49,873
you know, art is beautiful.

452
00:52:50,013 --> 00:52:56,374
Maybe it could be something where the art is interchangeable, you know, twice a year or something like that.

453
00:52:56,434 --> 00:52:58,315
They could switch it up for the seasons.

454
00:52:58,855 --> 00:53:09,457
And so I'm thinking that there could definitely be a lot of creative ways to have that community footprint and have it beautify the space through the arts.

455
00:53:10,077 --> 00:53:14,117
So I just wanted to share that as a possible suggestion.

456
00:53:19,264 --> 00:53:35,437
So I am, as I'm listening to everybody's comments, I'm wondering if our recommendation to the school committee is that we invite donors to donate and plan for a plaque that recognizes them.

457
00:53:35,517 --> 00:53:46,066
And maybe we come up with like a gold, silver, bronze sort of sponsorship level, or maybe we come up with more playground oriented names for those levels.

458
00:53:47,852 --> 00:53:49,933
And which I think might be fine.

459
00:53:50,353 --> 00:54:15,303
Um, so maybe we could, uh, think through that, um, and, um, Encourage, you know, those donations, you know, and note that, um, we'll have a commemorative plaque that would, you know, identify them and, um, leave it at that for, for our recommendation for the playground.

460
00:54:15,423 --> 00:54:15,723
I think.

461
00:54:16,352 --> 00:54:36,739
you know, to Dr. Cushing's point, like rounding off the playground to make sure that like, it has bike racks and, you know, all, you know, all the like little things that add up, or if we are able to, you know, raise some more money, we probably could plant more mature trees than what the trees are that we're going to be able to plant under the basic budget.

462
00:54:36,759 --> 00:54:43,281
So some of those things, I think, make it make sense for us to go ahead and try to,

463
00:54:45,502 --> 00:55:01,749
raise money, I think there's also going to be some disruption during the building of the playground where we're going to need to provide some equipment for students so that they have adequate play access while the playground is under construction that costs money.

464
00:55:01,769 --> 00:55:05,690
I don't believe that's in the estimate, Dr. Cushing, but I could be wrong.

465
00:55:06,210 --> 00:55:12,473
So there are reasons to raise money beyond the sort of estimate that

466
00:55:12,856 --> 00:55:18,638
The city has committed to, and it's, it's amazing that the city has committed to this.

467
00:55:18,959 --> 00:55:30,523
And I'm always reminded in these moments that sometimes out of really terrible things like COVID come things like ARPA money and new playgrounds.

468
00:55:30,563 --> 00:55:38,767
So, um, hopefully, um, that holds, um, particularly as construction costs rise, but I, I,

469
00:55:40,072 --> 00:56:06,081
That's sort of where I'm at in terms of the conversation I've just heard is do we establish some levels and promise plaque that would provide us the sort of space and the leeway to round out the playground and put out that call for public schools, from the superintendent's office to be able to do that.

470
00:56:06,201 --> 00:56:07,642
So I don't know.

471
00:56:09,427 --> 00:56:13,450
what you all think about that proposal, but that could be something that we push forward.

472
00:56:15,871 --> 00:56:16,612
I like that idea.

473
00:56:17,112 --> 00:56:17,933
I would agree with that.

474
00:56:18,914 --> 00:56:19,294
OK.

475
00:56:22,376 --> 00:56:27,900
Are there any thoughts about those threshold levels that we would?

476
00:56:29,081 --> 00:56:33,163
I mean, I think if you're going to put everybody on a plaque, it could be very long.

477
00:56:33,183 --> 00:56:36,466
If any dollar amount

478
00:56:38,767 --> 00:56:39,488
ends up on the plaque.

479
00:56:39,528 --> 00:56:41,489
I don't know if we have any immediate thoughts.

480
00:56:41,930 --> 00:56:47,454
I'm also happy just to put a draft out there and see what the committee thinks about it too.

481
00:56:47,614 --> 00:56:49,836
I know it is 5.30 and we're at our meeting time.

482
00:56:52,038 --> 00:56:53,939
I think you should probably have four levels.

483
00:56:54,119 --> 00:56:57,262
You should just include a platinum level because you never know.

484
00:56:57,842 --> 00:57:05,528
You may have a extra generous person who wants to give at that level and

485
00:57:07,896 --> 00:57:16,961
If people are willing to do that to support the schools, to support the community, I think we should recognize them.

486
00:57:17,501 --> 00:57:25,745
I don't know what the monetary amounts would be, if it would be like 10,000, 25,000, 50,000, and 100,000 plus or something.

487
00:57:25,765 --> 00:57:27,426
I don't know how you'd want to do that.

488
00:57:38,055 --> 00:57:42,921
If people are willing to be generous, they could be spending the money on

489
00:57:45,170 --> 00:57:55,014
a trip around the world or something else, if they're willing to give back to the community, I feel strongly that we should be able to acknowledge them.

490
00:57:55,834 --> 00:58:04,138
And, you know, we may end up with so much that there's extra money to go towards another playground.

491
00:58:04,678 --> 00:58:05,859
I mean, wouldn't that be wonderful?

492
00:58:06,599 --> 00:58:12,601
And put that in that, you know, if we reach whatever the goal is, whatever the magic number is that,

493
00:58:14,968 --> 00:58:26,594
people wanna get to, if we reach that number, then say, you know what, let's tackle the next playground that's in desperate need of an upgrade or something like that.

494
00:58:26,614 --> 00:58:30,456
Okay.

495
00:58:32,597 --> 00:58:38,440
Any last thoughts on dollar thresholds?

496
00:58:47,351 --> 00:58:47,611
Okay.

497
00:58:48,252 --> 00:58:50,493
Um, I will.

498
00:58:50,693 --> 00:59:07,504
So I think, um, this conversation obviously like in the minutes, um, and in the description of, um, the, um, the readout of the subcommittee meeting will sort of provide people some of the things that we've already thought about.

499
00:59:08,125 --> 00:59:14,809
I will put, um, an agenda item on a resolution on that lays out.

500
00:59:16,089 --> 00:59:19,030
some idea of what that set of thresholds might be.

501
00:59:19,130 --> 00:59:21,752
I'll actually take a look around and see what others have done.

502
00:59:22,272 --> 00:59:28,975
And then we can wordsmith it and all of that good stuff with the larger committee.

503
00:59:30,175 --> 00:59:32,116
So I don't think we need to take a vote on any of that.

504
00:59:32,997 --> 00:59:37,739
And with that, do I hear a motion to adjourn?

505
00:59:37,759 --> 00:59:40,400
Motion to adjourn.

506
00:59:41,060 --> 00:59:41,300
Second.

507
00:59:42,241 --> 00:59:44,862
Motion to adjourn by member Hayes, seconded by member So.

